Set to Y to use DB Link
Default N
This parameter indicates a DB Link has been created in the warehouse database that can be used to extract data from the source system. If set to Y, a DB Link is used to transfer data from the source. This is applicable only when the source and target are on compatible Oracle Versions. If set to N, the data is extracted via JDBC.
The ETL process does not create a DB Link. It instead assumes that a db link already exists with the following naming convention:
<DATASERVER_NAME>.WORLD@DSN_<DSN_ID>
So if the Dataserver name for EBS is EBS11510 and the DSN for EBS11510 is 310, then the db link name should be EBS11510.WORLD@DSN_310
This DB Link should exist in the warehouse and be accessible using the warehouse credentials.

This variable is used by the Clean Work and Flow Tables procedure. Any work/flow tables older than the number of days specified by this variables are dropped by the procedure.
This would result in cleaning up of any stray work/flow tables left over in the datawarehouse due to failed mappings.

List of Alter session Commands Do not include the Alter SEssion keywords. For multiple commands seperate them by semicolon.
E.g. : If you want to run the following two commands
alter session set TRACEFILE_IDENTIFIER='ODI_TRACE' alter session set events '10046 TRACE NAME CONTEXT FOREVER, LEVEL 8'
enter the value as
set TRACEFILE_IDENTIFIER='ODI_TRACE'; set events '10046 TRACE NAME CONTEXT FOREVER, LEVEL 8';
Default value for this variable is NOT_APPLICABLE which implies that no commands need to be passed for Alter session.

Variable indicating that a Source dependent Data Store (SDS) has been created and is being populated via GoldenGate. This variable is evaluated by individual ETL processes to determine if logic that requires the SDS can be executed or not. Valid values are 'Y' (is deployed) and 'N' (is not deployed).

Number of days prior to the last ETL run to include in the ETL extract window. Used in calculating LAST_EXTRACT_DATE which identifies those records to be extracted in an incremental ETL run. Essentially extends the window of time for records to be evaluated for extraction beyond just those that have changed or were created since the last ETL run.
This is a global variable set in Configuration Manager. Being a global variable, it impacts all ETL runs.
